    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="691"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d691">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 814.51/181.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Kineo, Maine</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 29, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I communicated substance of your letter of September 21st to my Government and in
                    reply I am instructed to point out that while His Majesty’s Government has no
                    objections granting of a <pb facs="0621" n="505" xml:id="pg_505"/> delay of
                    twenty days from seventeenth instant, they do not desire a settlement of any
                    kind but the restitution to the bondholders of the revenue through [sic] which
                    they are undoubtedly entitled under loan contract.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryce.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
